Use conditional compilation directives in `MauiProgram.cs` to register each platform's implementation:

```csharp
public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
{
    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

#if ANDROID
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Android.AndroidNotificationService>();
#elif IOS
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.iOS.iOSNotificationService>();
#elif WINDOWS
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Windows.WindowsNotificationService>();
#endif

    return builder.Build();
}
```

Each implementation lives under its respective `Platforms/` folder (which is already per-platform compiled by the SDK). The preprocessor symbols (`ANDROID`, `IOS`, `WINDOWS`) are defined automatically by the MAUI build targets, so only the relevant registration compiles for each platform—nothing breaks on the others.

**Alternative (no `#if`):** Place the registration in a partial class method with platform-specific partial implementations under each `Platforms/` folder, letting the SDK's per-platform file inclusion handle it automatically.
